# proxy.ts and Auth

`proxy.ts` (v16+) sits at the edge of your app and runs on every matching request. It is the right place for OPTIMISTIC checks (read a session cookie, redirect unauthenticated traffic away from `/dashboard/*`). It is the WRONG place for the security boundary.

This rule covers the file shape, the three-layer auth model Vercel recommends, and the LLM-trap patterns around proxy / context / cookies.

## `middleware.ts` -> `proxy.ts` (v16+)

The file was renamed and the exported function name changed.

```typescript
// BAD (new code, v16) - middleware.ts is deprecated
// middleware.ts
import { NextResponse } from 'next/server';
import type { NextRequest } from 'next/server';

export function middleware(req: NextRequest) {
  return NextResponse.next();
}

// CORRECT - proxy.ts
// proxy.ts (at the project root, same place middleware.ts lived)
import { NextResponse } from 'next/server';
import type { NextRequest } from 'next/server';

export function proxy(req: NextRequest) {
  return NextResponse.next();
}

export const config = {
  matcher: [
    // Apply to everything EXCEPT next-internal, static assets, the favicon
    '/((?!_next/static|_next/image|favicon.ico|.*\\.(?:png|jpg|jpeg|svg|webp|css|js)$).*)',
  ],
};
```

Key v16 deltas:

- File name: `middleware.ts` -> `proxy.ts`
- Function name: `middleware` -> `proxy`
- Runtime: `proxy.ts` runs on Node.js runtime only. The Edge-only `middleware.ts` form still works for the legacy Edge case but is deprecated.
- Config flag: `skipMiddlewareUrlNormalize` -> `skipProxyUrlNormalize`

```typescript
// next.config.ts
import type { NextConfig } from 'next';

const config: NextConfig = {
  // v15
  // skipMiddlewareUrlNormalize: true,

  // v16
  skipProxyUrlNormalize: true,
};

export default config;
```

## The matcher

`config.matcher` accepts a string, array of strings, or array of objects. Patterns use the path-to-regexp syntax familiar from Express.

```typescript
export const config = {
  matcher: [
    '/dashboard/:path*',
    '/admin/:path*',
    {
      source: '/api/:path*',
      missing: [{ type: 'header', key: 'x-internal' }],
    },
  ],
};
```

A request that does not match the config is never run through `proxy.ts` at all.

## The three-layer auth model

This is Vercel's officially documented pattern. Each layer has a single job; together they are defense in depth.

```
Layer 1: proxy.ts          OPTIMISTIC check (read cookie, early redirect)
                          - Reads cookie value only, never hits the DB
                          - Runs on prefetched routes too; cannot be trusted
                          - Purpose: avoid sending unauthenticated traffic
                            deeper into the app

Layer 2: DAL verifySession  SECURE check (hits session store)
                          - cache()-wrapped, runs once per render pass
                          - Verifies the cookie token against the DB / KV
                          - Returns a typed Session or null

Layer 3: Component + Action  Always re-verify inside DAL functions and
                            inside every Server Action
                          - Defense in depth at the data layer
```

> Rule: never trust proxy.ts. Always re-verify in the DAL.

## Layer 1: proxy.ts (optimistic only)

```typescript
// proxy.ts
import { NextResponse } from 'next/server';
import type { NextRequest } from 'next/server';

const PROTECTED_PREFIXES = ['/dashboard', '/admin', '/settings'];
const PUBLIC_AUTH_ROUTES = ['/login', '/signup'];

export function proxy(req: NextRequest) {
  const { pathname } = req.nextUrl;
  const sessionCookie = req.cookies.get('session')?.value;

  // OPTIMISTIC: just looks at cookie presence. Does NOT verify the token.
  const looksAuthenticated = Boolean(sessionCookie);

  // Redirect unauthenticated traffic away from protected routes
  if (PROTECTED_PREFIXES.some(p => pathname.startsWith(p)) && !looksAuthenticated) {
    const url = req.nextUrl.clone();
    url.pathname = '/login';
    url.searchParams.set('next', pathname);
    return NextResponse.redirect(url);
  }

  // Redirect authenticated traffic away from login / signup
  if (PUBLIC_AUTH_ROUTES.includes(pathname) && looksAuthenticated) {
    const url = req.nextUrl.clone();
    url.pathname = '/dashboard';
    return NextResponse.redirect(url);
  }

  return NextResponse.next();
}

export const config = {
  matcher: [
    '/((?!_next/static|_next/image|favicon.ico|.*\\.(?:png|jpg|jpeg|svg|webp)$).*)',
  ],
};
```

What this does and does not do:

- DOES: redirect cheaply when the cookie is missing entirely.
- DOES: redirect already-signed-in users away from the login page.
- DOES NOT: validate the cookie. A forged cookie passes this check.
- DOES NOT: hit the database. A DB call in `proxy.ts` runs on every request including prefetches.
- DOES NOT: protect the action endpoints. A direct POST to an action ID bypasses `proxy.ts` entirely.

## Layer 2: DAL `verifySession` (secure)

```typescript
// lib/dal/index.ts
import 'server-only';
import { cache } from 'react';
import { cookies } from 'next/headers';
import { db } from '@/lib/db';

export type Session = {
  userId: string;
  role: 'user' | 'admin';
  expiresAt: Date;
};

export const verifySession = cache(async (): Promise<Session | null> => {
  const cookieStore = await cookies();
  const token = cookieStore.get('session')?.value;
  if (!token) return null;

  const session = await db.session.findUnique({
    where: { token },
    select: { userId: true, role: true, expiresAt: true },
  });
  if (!session) return null;
  if (session.expiresAt < new Date()) return null;
  return session;
});
```

See `nextjs-data-access-layer` for the full pattern.

## Layer 3: re-verify in every consumer

```typescript
// Server Component
export default async function DashboardPage() {
  const session = await verifySession();
  if (!session) redirect('/login');
  // ...
}
```

```typescript
// Server Action
'use server';
export async function deletePost(id: string) {
  const session = await verifySession();
  if (!session) throw new Error('Unauthorized');
  // ... resource ownership check, then mutation
}
```

```typescript
// Route Handler
export async function POST(req: Request) {
  const session = await verifySession();
  if (!session) return NextResponse.json({ error: 'Unauthorized' }, { status: 401 });
  // ...
}
```

## Why `proxy.ts` is NEVER the security boundary

Three specific reasons LLMs trip over:

1. **`proxy.ts` runs on prefetched routes.** Next.js prefetches `<Link>` targets in the background. The prefetch goes through `proxy.ts` too. Doing real authorization work in `proxy.ts` causes either (a) wasted database calls on every prefetch or (b) auth state being asserted for routes the user never actually visited.

2. **Server Actions have addressable POST endpoints.** Every Server Action gets an encrypted ID. An attacker who scrapes the ID from the network tab can POST directly to your app. That POST might match `proxy.ts`'s matcher or might not - and even when it does, `proxy.ts` cannot inspect which action is being invoked or what resource it touches.

3. **Route Handlers and direct fetches.** External callers (webhooks, mobile clients, internal services) hit Route Handlers directly. If the Route Handler trusts a header set by `proxy.ts`, anyone can forge that header on a request that bypasses the matcher.

The fix is the same in all three cases: re-verify at the data layer. `verifySession` inside the DAL function, inside the action, inside the route handler. The cookie-check in `proxy.ts` exists purely to avoid the wasted work of rendering an unauthenticated dashboard.

## Cookie discipline

Session cookies live on the SERVER. Set them in a Server Action, a Route Handler, or `proxy.ts`. Never `document.cookie =` from the client.

```typescript
// BAD - client-side cookie set
'use client';
function signIn() {
  document.cookie = `session=${token}; path=/`;
}

// CORRECT - server-side cookie set inside a Server Action
'use server';
import { cookies } from 'next/headers';

export async function signIn(_prev: State, formData: FormData) {
  // ... validate credentials, mint session token

  const cookieStore = await cookies();
  cookieStore.set('session', token, {
    httpOnly: true,         // not readable from JS - blocks XSS exfiltration
    secure: true,           // HTTPS only
    sameSite: 'lax',        // mitigates CSRF; 'strict' for higher-stakes apps
    path: '/',
    expires: new Date(Date.now() + 7 * 24 * 60 * 60 * 1000),
  });

  redirect('/dashboard');
}
```

Cookie flag rationale:

- `httpOnly: true` - the cookie is invisible to `document.cookie`. An XSS payload cannot exfiltrate it.
- `secure: true` - the browser only sends the cookie over HTTPS. Mandatory in production.
- `sameSite: 'lax'` - default for most apps. Browser sends the cookie on top-level navigation but not on cross-site POSTs. Use `'strict'` if you do not need cross-site GETs (e.g. payment links).
- `path: '/'` - cookie scoped to the whole app. Narrow this only if you have a specific reason.

Setting cookies is forbidden during render. The setter only works in a Server Action, Route Handler, or `proxy.ts`.

```typescript
// BAD - throws "Cookies can only be modified in a Server Action or Route Handler"
export default async function Page() {
  const cookieStore = await cookies();
  cookieStore.set('seen', '1');  // forbidden during render
  return <div />;
}
```

## Auth.js v5 (NextAuth) shape

Auth.js v5 (formerly NextAuth) is the most common auth library in the Next.js ecosystem. The v5 export shape:

```typescript
// lib/auth.ts
import NextAuth from 'next-auth';
import GitHub from 'next-auth/providers/github';

export const { auth, signIn, signOut, handlers } = NextAuth({
  providers: [GitHub],
  session: { strategy: 'jwt' },
});
```

Then in Server Components and actions:

```typescript
import { auth } from '@/lib/auth';

export default async function Page() {
  const session = await auth();
  if (!session) redirect('/login');
  return <div>Hi {session.user.name}</div>;
}
```

In a Route Handler:

```typescript
// app/api/auth/[...nextauth]/route.ts
import { handlers } from '@/lib/auth';
export const { GET, POST } = handlers;
```

Auth.js v5 wires into `proxy.ts` via `auth` as a wrapper - but the same rule applies: the wrapper does the cookie check optimistically. Re-verify in the DAL.

## Other auth library options

All function as Vercel-equivalent alternatives. Verify against your installed version's docs for the exact shape:

- **Clerk** - hosted auth + UI components, generous free tier
- **Better Auth** - self-hosted, framework-agnostic, growing community
- **WorkOS** - enterprise SSO, SAML, SCIM
- **Stack Auth** - open source, full-stack
- **Supabase Auth** - bundled with Supabase DB, JWT-based
- **Stytch** - passwordless / OTP focus

The integration pattern is the same in each: a server-side `verifySession`-equivalent in the DAL, optimistic redirects in `proxy.ts`, re-verification in every action.

## React Context does NOT work for auth in Server Components

A `<SessionProvider value={...}>` that wraps a Server Component child does NOT propagate the context to that child. Server Components have no React Context runtime.

```typescript
// BAD - context never reaches the Server Component child
'use client';
const SessionContext = createContext<Session | null>(null);
export function SessionProvider({ value, children }: Props) {
  return <SessionContext.Provider value={value}>{children}</SessionContext.Provider>;
}

// Somewhere:
<SessionProvider value={session}>
  <ServerDashboard /> {/* renders WITHOUT context, gets null */}
</SessionProvider>
```

```typescript
// CORRECT - read session at the server component itself
import { verifySession } from '@/lib/dal';

export default async function ServerDashboard() {
  const session = await verifySession();
  if (!session) redirect('/login');
  return <Dashboard userId={session.userId} />;
}
```

For Client Components that need session info, pass the minimum necessary fields down as props from a Server Component, or use a Client-side context whose provider only wraps Client Components.

## `taintUniqueValue` for safe session exposure

If you must hand session info to a Client Component, hand only what is safe - and taint the original so an accidental leak throws.

```typescript
// lib/dal/index.ts
import 'server-only';
import { experimental_taintUniqueValue as taintUniqueValue } from 'react';

export const verifySession = cache(async () => {
  // ... fetch session
  const session = { userId, role, expiresAt, token };

  // Taint the token so it can never reach a Client Component
  taintUniqueValue(
    'Do not pass the session token to the client',
    session,
    session.token
  );

  return session;
});
```

If `session.token` ever lands in a Client Component prop, React throws. The `userId` and `role` fields are safe to pass.

`taintUniqueValue` is gated behind the `experimental.taint` flag. Verify against your installed version's changelog before adopting.

## Common mistakes

- **Trusting `proxy.ts` as the security boundary.** It runs on prefetches; it cannot inspect action IDs; a direct POST bypasses it. Always re-verify in the DAL.
- **No `verifySession` re-check inside a Server Action.** Page-level auth does not extend to the action. Actions are addressable POST endpoints.
- **Hitting the database inside `proxy.ts`.** Runs on every prefetched route. Either drop the DB call or move the check to the DAL.
- **Redirecting from `proxy.ts` for cases that belong in the Server Component.** If the redirect depends on user state more nuanced than "has a session cookie," do it server-side.
- **React Context for session in Server Components.** Providers do not propagate to Server children. Read session from the DAL on the server.
- **Setting cookies on the client.** Use a Server Action or Route Handler. Mark cookies `httpOnly: true, secure: true, sameSite: 'lax'`.
- **`cookies().set(...)` during render.** Forbidden. Only mutate cookies in a Server Action, Route Handler, or `proxy.ts`.
- **Forgetting the `skipMiddlewareUrlNormalize` -> `skipProxyUrlNormalize` rename.** The v15 flag silently does nothing in v16.
- **Keeping `middleware.ts` for new v16 code.** The Edge-runtime `middleware.ts` still works but is deprecated. Default to `proxy.ts`.
